    • Vinay Jha Chhandogy-upanishada (which is part of Talwaakaara shaakhaa of Saamaveda and is therefore part of Veda) clearly states that shudra must not recite Vedic mantras because if shudra does so he/she will be harmed. Modern anti-Vedic idiots spread a lie that brahmins did not want to allow shudras from studying anything. It is a lie. Only mantra-vidya was restricted to dvijas. But brahmins and Kshatriyas in those days were far more pure than they are today. Shudra did not imply caste, Chhandogy-upanishada states that "shudra" denotes a person who deliberately runs after things which ultimately give sorrow. Brahmin was defined as one having Brahm-gyaana. There is no casteism in these views. They were varnas based on karma.
